    slug: "openai-gpt-5-4-cyber-anthropic-mythos-split-april-2026",
    title: "OpenAI Built a Less-Restricted AI Model for Security Teams. Anthropic Went the Other Direction.",
    summary: "OpenAI's GPT-5.4-Cyber rolled out April 14 to thousands of verified defenders. Anthropic's Mythos went to about 40 organizations. Two labs looked at the same capability tier and drew opposite conclusions.",
    body: [
      "Six days apart. On April 8, Anthropic confirmed its most capable model, Claude Mythos, would not be publicly released, with access restricted to roughly 40 partners under Project Glasswing. On April 14, OpenAI announced GPT-5.4-Cyber, a version of its frontier model with relaxed restrictions for legitimate security work, and rolled it out to thousands of verified defenders through a program called Trusted Access for Cyber.",
      "Read those two decisions together and the disagreement is explicit. Anthropic concluded that a model capable of autonomous vulnerability discovery and exploit chaining was too dangerous to distribute widely, regardless of the caller's stated purpose. OpenAI concluded that the right answer to dangerous capability is not scarcity, but verification — make sure the caller is who they say they are, and then let the capability serve defense at scale.",
      "Both positions have force. Anthropic's is the more conservative call, and the one that holds up if something goes wrong downstream: if a restricted-tier model gets used to automate mass-scale intrusion, the lab that shipped it to thousands of customers is the one at the hearing. OpenAI's is the more operationally honest call: attackers don't wait for approval to use AI tooling, and the defensive side of the asymmetry has been outpaced for two years. Getting capable tools into the hands of defenders at a scale that matches the threat is worth the verification overhead.",
      "The quiet part is that both companies appear to believe the underlying capability threshold has actually been crossed. Neither is shipping its best model into the public API with default safety training. Both have converged on gated-access programs tied to identity verification. The disagreement is about how wide the gate is, not whether there should be one.",
      "For security teams, the immediate question is which program your organization qualifies for and which one actually improves your defensive posture. The OpenAI program is easier to get into and covers thousands of organizations. The Anthropic program is smaller, tighter, and reportedly pairs access with direct partnership support. A third interesting question: what happens when the next tier above both of these gets built. Neither company has committed to what they'll do at that point, and the answers they give in April 2027 are going to matter more than the ones they're giving now.",
    ],
