    id: 38,
    slug: "nist-nvd-cve-enrichment-changes-2026",
    title: "NIST Is Giving Up on Fully Enriching Every CVE. Your Patch Management Probably Depends on That.",
    summary: "The National Vulnerability Database will now prioritize enrichment instead of covering everything. Teams that treated NVD as the authoritative source just got a new dependency problem.",
    body: [
      "NIST announced this week that the National Vulnerability Database is changing how it handles CVEs — prioritizing enrichment for a subset of submissions rather than attempting full coverage. The stated driver: a 263% surge in CVE submissions between 2020 and 2025. The team simply can't keep up.",
      "If you've built your vulnerability management program on NVD data — and most organizations have, because it's been the authoritative free source for CVSS scores, CPE mappings, and structured metadata — this affects you directly.",
      "The practical consequence: some CVEs will appear in NVD with limited enrichment. No CPE match strings. No CVSS vector string. Maybe no severity at all. Your scanner or SBOM tool that joins against NVD to decide what's critical will miss things or return nulls. The gap is going to land hardest on mid-tier vendors and open-source libraries, where CNA submissions are often sparse to begin with.",
      "There's a reasonable counter-argument to make here — NVD was never going to scale linearly with CVE volume, and fully enriching every low-quality submission was diluting the signal of the serious ones. Prioritization might produce better data on the CVEs that actually matter. We'll see.",
      "What to do this week: audit where your vulnerability workflow treats NVD as a single source of truth. Cross-reference against CISA KEV, vendor advisories, and at least one commercial feed (Tenable, Qualys, Snyk, whoever you already pay) so you're not blind on any CVE that NVD deprioritizes. The days of a free, complete, structured CVE database are ending, and you need an answer for that before your next audit.",
      "One quiet note: this also puts more pressure on CISA's KEV catalog as the thing federal agencies and serious private-sector programs actually trigger patching off of. KEV is curated, conservative, and only covers actively exploited bugs — which is exactly why it's been more operationally useful than NVD for years anyway.",
    ],
