    id: 35,
    slug: "cisco-ise-webex-critical-rce-cvss-9-9-april-2026",
    title: "Four Critical CVEs in Cisco ISE and Webex, Three of Them at CVSS 9.9",
    summary: "CVE-2026-20147 gives an attacker with read-only ISE admin credentials a path to root on your network access control infrastructure, and CVE-2026-20184 lets anyone impersonate Webex users without authentication.",
    body: [
      "Three CVSS 9.9 scores in one advisory. Cisco's patch release this week for Identity Services Engine and Webex is not a routine item. CVSS 9.9 means remote code execution escalating to root with no physical interaction required, and three of the four critical vulnerabilities here reach it.",
      "CVE-2026-20147, CVE-2026-20180, and CVE-2026-20186 all stem from the same root problem: insufficient input validation in the ISE web administration interface. The authentication bar is low. An attacker needs valid ISE credentials, but read-only administrative access is enough — the kind of access a compromised help desk account or a disgruntled contractor would hold. From there, a crafted HTTP request reaches the ISE node, code runs, and the attacker escalates to root on the underlying OS. Cisco's advisory confirms the escalation path.",
      "Why that matters specifically: Cisco ISE is the network access control backbone for most large enterprise environments. It handles 802.1X authentication for every wired and wireless endpoint. Root on ISE means an attacker can manipulate which devices are allowed onto the network, issue certificates, intercept authentication flows, and pivot anywhere in the environment. Shodan queries shared by researchers show around 812 ISE appliances currently internet-exposed.",
      "CVE-2026-20184 in Webex is a separate flaw rated CVSS 9.8. It affects how the SSO integration validates certificates against Cisco's Control Hub. An unauthenticated remote attacker can impersonate any user in a Webex deployment. Cisco has patched its cloud infrastructure, but organizations using SSO must manually upload a new identity provider SAML certificate to Control Hub. That step is not automatic. If your Webex deployment uses SSO and you have not done this, user impersonation is open.",
      "Cisco has not confirmed exploitation in the wild. There are no workarounds for any of the four CVEs. Patch versions: ISE 3.1 requires patch 11; ISE 3.2 requires patch 10; ISE 3.3 requires patch 10; ISE 3.4 requires patch 6; ISE 3.5 requires patch 3. The Webex SAML certificate upload procedure is documented in Cisco's advisory for CVE-2026-20184.",
    ],
